## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis 1: every tool that takes a directory-scope argument
  must expose it explicitly in the JSON schema. Models cannot pass
  args that aren't in the contract; they will mangle the
  available knobs trying to compensate (the model in the wire
  trace tried encoding scope inside file_pattern as
  **/define.scm — meaningless but well-intentioned).
- Hypothesis 2: --include= is widely misunderstood as a path
  glob. Documenting it as a BASENAME glob in the schema
  description prevents the model from trying to put slashes in.
- Hypothesis 3: head -50 was masking the scope problem because
  whichever directory grep walked first filled the window. Even
  raising to head -200 isn't a real fix; the right fix is to make
  scoping work so the truncation is rarely hit.

## Validation
- Phase 1 reproduced the bug with a natural prompt (\"Search for
  define in src/sage\"); the model emitted no path key.
- Phase 2 quoted the exact JSON the model emitted from the
  http.jsonl wire trace — proves the schema is the bottleneck.
- Phase 3 forced the explicit \"path=src/sage\" prompt; the model
  STILL couldn't pass path because the schema lacked it. Strong
  evidence that the schema is the only lever.
- Phase 4 (direct execute-tool) confirmed: passing path=src/sage
  to the OLD tool was silently dropped because the body never
  read the arg. Same byte-for-byte output as no-arg call.
- Post-fix smoke test: scope works, unsafe path rejected,
  no-scope fallback still works.

## Refutation / known limits
- head -200 is still arbitrary truncation. A model that asks for
  every match of a common pattern will lose results. A real fix
  would either remove the cap or paginate. Out of scope for this
  bug.
- file_pattern is still --include=, which is documented as a
  basename glob in the new schema description, but the model has
  no way to enforce a path glob. If a user wants \"src/sage/util.scm\"
  they have to use path=src/sage + file_pattern=util.scm.
- The grep command is shell-formatted. If pattern contains
  single quotes the substitution breaks. Existing parity with
  the rest of tools.scm — sage uses sh-quoted grep elsewhere
  too — and is tracked separately under guile-sage-eeh
  (guile-curl + native subprocess migration).
- No PBT property yet for the new path arg. Filed as a follow-up
  in this same stack — will land in commit 3 of this stack.

